{{technology-stub}}

A [[flame]] may exhibit intrinsic instabilities of several kinds when one or more of the physico-chemical balances associated with its propagation is offset. In [[premixed flame]]s, the primary instability is a hydrodynamic instability — known as the Darrieus-Landau instability — which results from thermal expansion across the flame interface.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Matalon|first=Moshe|date=2006-12-20|title=Intrinsic Flame Instabilities in Premixed and Nonpremixed Combustion|url=http://annualreviews.org/doi/abs/10.1146/annurev.fluid.38.050304.092153|journal=Annual Review of Fluid Mechanics|language=en|volume=39|issue=1|pages=163–191|doi=10.1146/annurev.fluid.38.050304.092153}}</ref> In [[Diffusion flame|non-premixed (diffusion) flames]], thermo-diffusive instabilities are predominant while the hydrodynamic instability plays a secondary role.

